    },
    {
      "id": "oZsOn_LMwt_PD7XDcbfNV",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1843.7530879956148,
      "y": 2013.592585910842,
      "width": 1269.5791015625,
      "height": 500,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b0X",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1556973416,
      "version": 1523,
      "versionNonce": 477580224,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1776357726509,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "How do we make sure Offline delivery/access of Messages\n    - 2 new entites we need:\n        1. messages -> keep track of the content of a message.\n        2. Index -> it's like a queue that tracks the message deliverables\n    \n    Flow:\n       - So the client send a message to a chat with some Id to chat-service.\n       - Chat-service will look into chatParticipants to find list or participants for that chatId.\n       - The message will be with the message enity -> and an entry is added to Indox.\n       - 2 cases:\n           1. Recipient is offline.\n                - If the guy is offline, messages keeps queing up in Inbox.\n                - The moment my guy connects -> Chat service -> Offloads all messages corresponding to his recipientId from Inbox.\n                - Once Deliveries and client service receive confirmation from client -> clear recrods from Inbox\n\n           2. Recipient is online:\n               - In this case, client service checks the corresponding WS connection and sends the message back.\n               - Once the message is received -> we remove the entry from the Inbox -> Guarenties Delivery. \n\n    This gurantees messages are eventually delivered to the client. ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "How do we make sure Offline delivery/access of Messages\n    - 2 new entites we need:\n        1. messages -> keep track of the content of a message.\n        2. Index -> it's like a queue that tracks the message deliverables\n    \n    Flow:\n       - So the client send a message to a chat with some Id to chat-service.\n       - Chat-service will look into chatParticipants to find list or participants for that chatId.\n       - The message will be with the message enity -> and an entry is added to Indox.\n       - 2 cases:\n           1. Recipient is offline.\n                - If the guy is offline, messages keeps queing up in Inbox.\n                - The moment my guy connects -> Chat service -> Offloads all messages corresponding to his recipientId from Inbox.\n                - Once Deliveries and client service receive confirmation from client -> clear recrods from Inbox\n\n           2. Recipient is online:\n               - In this case, client service checks the corresponding WS connection and sends the message back.\n               - Once the message is received -> we remove the entry from the Inbox -> Guarenties Delivery. \n\n    This gurantees messages are eventually delivered to the client. ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "Qu_ANtXdKBGq2CS7NjhhK",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -592.9103414397794,
      "y": 1899.4258423388337,
      "width": 1708.1190185546875,
      "height": 1600,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b0Y",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 594592792,
      "version": 5500,
      "versionNonce": 1093452736,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1776357906257,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Latency of messages:\n    - it's already set as we are writing our messages in database and \n      using websockets to connect our services with client. \nGuarntee Message DElivery:\n    - we have a table with inbox that tracks the messages deliveries.\n    - In case of user is offline -> it stores messages and sed them when he comes back online.\n\nScalability of the systm\n    - It needs to handle 2M + chat interactions and that's a very high number.\n    - We need a lot of like in 100s or 1000s instances of chat services to handle that many interations\n    - ways:\n      1. using Load Balancer to manage traffic:\n          Problem:\n                - In a web server like with HTTP, that are stateless so in L7 layer (HTTP Layer) LB, it can send that\n                  traffic to any running instance of our chat service. [ no-issues at all ]\n                - But the problem with websockets connection --> They need to presisit between the client and server.\n          Solution:\n                - We need a L4 Load Balancer.\n                - When the client connects to a LB, it creates a TCP conncetion. [send messages over it], LB also connects\n                   to chat service.\n                - The Load balancer becomes invisible to chat service.\n                - LB can decidie which Client can be connected to which server. The choosing algo can be Least open Connection.\n                  Connect to the server that is least in use.\n           Cons:\n                - It helps in horizontal scaling. good ! But it kind of breaks the latency of messages flow takes a hit.\n                  user A might be on Server instance 1, user B might be on Server instance 2 -> One chat spreading across server instances.\n            \n                  We have a Routing Problem here !!!\n                \n                way1: Subscribing to Kafaka Topic:\n                     -  You want to write a message -> server finds all relevant participants -> write it Kafka topic for each User.\n                     - Then chat services can subscribe and read from those topics and they will have the messages and send back to client.\n\n                    Problem: \n                    - Kafka is not build to handle billions of users !! There topics are also heavy (50 -100 kb per topic) -> for billions of users -> it's TBs of data.\n                    - Kafka doesnot support rapid connect & disconnect of topic.\n                \n     2. Consitent HashRing:\n            - EXpose the Client server directly to client via web DNS.  Introduce a chat Registry [ For Client to find out which Chat server thy need to connect ]\n            - use \"ZooKeeper\" to track which user is assigned to which server !\n            - Message Flow now:\n              User A a client -> goes to Chat Registy and ask for which server he is connected to ? -> It returns server 1.\n              Now when they try to send a message to user B -> they write their message to server 1  which they are connected to.\n              From Zookeeper, we get the information on which server user B might be available ? lets assume server 2. \n              Then, server1 will directly write the message to server 2. then server 2 check if userB actually connected ? if connected -> it will pass the message.\n\n        Cons:\n            - This hopping and tracking servers for users --> is pain while scaling.\n            - users on server can connect, disconnect, zookeeper takes time to sync these changes.\n            - the target user also we are not sure if present on server 2 or 3 -> so we send message to both -> then there the servers check if the user is actually connected.\n            - This adds additional friction in the scaling process !\n    \n     3. Redis Pub/Sub:\n            - when user connects to a chat server -> that chat server will register a subscription to Redis for that userId.\n            - When a client sends a message and we need to notify all connected user about it -> the chatService will publish a notification to that topic for that userId.\n            - Redis will pass that message to the client server responsible for those userId and that server pass that message over the web-socket with that userIds. \n                 \n        Cons:\n            - Scaling would be challenge for Redis cluster, move around topics.\n            - The topics will be schattered across the nodes of the Redis cluster --> the the chat server has to connect to each nodes.\n            - One Advantage is, The Redis cluster is not doing much, just echoing message to the right server. -> we don't need a giant cluster.\n\n    \n    Thus, These ways might help to maintain the flow of messages in case of system scaling but yes with some limitations ofc !",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Latency of messages:\n    - it's already set as we are writing our messages in database and \n      using websockets to connect our services with client. \nGuarntee Message DElivery:\n    - we have a table with inbox that tracks the messages deliveries.\n    - In case of user is offline -> it stores messages and sed them when he comes back online.\n\nScalability of the systm\n    - It needs to handle 2M + chat interactions and that's a very high number.\n    - We need a lot of like in 100s or 1000s instances of chat services to handle that many interations\n    - ways:\n      1. using Load Balancer to manage traffic:\n          Problem:\n                - In a web server like with HTTP, that are stateless so in L7 layer (HTTP Layer) LB, it can send that\n                  traffic to any running instance of our chat service. [ no-issues at all ]\n                - But the problem with websockets connection --> They need to presisit between the client and server.\n          Solution:\n                - We need a L4 Load Balancer.\n                - When the client connects to a LB, it creates a TCP conncetion. [send messages over it], LB also connects\n                   to chat service.\n                - The Load balancer becomes invisible to chat service.\n                - LB can decidie which Client can be connected to which server. The choosing algo can be Least open Connection.\n                  Connect to the server that is least in use.\n           Cons:\n                - It helps in horizontal scaling. good ! But it kind of breaks the latency of messages flow takes a hit.\n                  user A might be on Server instance 1, user B might be on Server instance 2 -> One chat spreading across server instances.\n            \n                  We have a Routing Problem here !!!\n                \n                way1: Subscribing to Kafaka Topic:\n                     -  You want to write a message -> server finds all relevant participants -> write it Kafka topic for each User.\n                     - Then chat services can subscribe and read from those topics and they will have the messages and send back to client.\n\n                    Problem: \n                    - Kafka is not build to handle billions of users !! There topics are also heavy (50 -100 kb per topic) -> for billions of users -> it's TBs of data.\n                    - Kafka doesnot support rapid connect & disconnect of topic.\n                \n     2. Consitent HashRing:\n            - EXpose the Client server directly to client via web DNS.  Introduce a chat Registry [ For Client to find out which Chat server thy need to connect ]\n            - use \"ZooKeeper\" to track which user is assigned to which server !\n            - Message Flow now:\n              User A a client -> goes to Chat Registy and ask for which server he is connected to ? -> It returns server 1.\n              Now when they try to send a message to user B -> they write their message to server 1  which they are connected to.\n              From Zookeeper, we get the information on which server user B might be available ? lets assume server 2. \n              Then, server1 will directly write the message to server 2. then server 2 check if userB actually connected ? if connected -> it will pass the message.\n\n        Cons:\n            - This hopping and tracking servers for users --> is pain while scaling.\n            - users on server can connect, disconnect, zookeeper takes time to sync these changes.\n            - the target user also we are not sure if present on server 2 or 3 -> so we send message to both -> then there the servers check if the user is actually connected.\n            - This adds additional friction in the scaling process !\n    \n     3. Redis Pub/Sub:\n            - when user connects to a chat server -> that chat server will register a subscription to Redis for that userId.\n            - When a client sends a message and we need to notify all connected user about it -> the chatService will publish a notification to that topic for that userId.\n            - Redis will pass that message to the client server responsible for those userId and that server pass that message over the web-socket with that userIds. \n                 \n        Cons:\n            - Scaling would be challenge for Redis cluster, move around topics.\n            - The topics will be schattered across the nodes of the Redis cluster --> the the chat server has to connect to each nodes.\n            - One Advantage is, The Redis cluster is not doing much, just echoing message to the right server. -> we don't need a giant cluster.\n\n    \n    Thus, These ways might help to maintain the flow of messages in case of system scaling but yes with some limitations ofc !",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "y7jepcltHD7j3d1mdx-bl",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -555.8453240912125,
      "y": 3612.8150703414376,
      "width": 1261.319091796875,
      "height": 125,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b0Z",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 772928448,
      "version": 530,
      "versionNonce": 463903680,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1776357907473,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "What we do for the messages that are stored unnecessarily ?\n\n- We can add a cleanUp Service  -> we can add a secondary index in Messages table [has timestamp column].\n- We can query messages over 30 days, and delete them.\n- The Inbox --> Going to have a record for every undelivered message -> It going to be delted as soon as the client received it.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "What we do for the messages that are stored unnecessarily ?\n\n- We can add a cleanUp Service  -> we can add a secondary index in Messages table [has timestamp column].\n- We can query messages over 30 days, and delete them.\n- The Inbox --> Going to have a record for every undelivered message -> It going to be delted as soon as the client received it.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
